import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

x = sns.load_dataset('tips')['total_bill']
q1, q2, q3 = x.quantile([.25, .5, .75])

B = (q1 + q3 - 2*q2) / (q3 - q1)

sns.boxplot(x=x)
plt.title(f"Bowley Skewness: {B:.2f}")
plt.show()



📊 Bowley’s Skewness — Definition & Theory
📌 Definition

Bowley’s coefficient of skewness is a measure of the asymmetry of a distribution based on quartiles.
Sk = (Q3 + Q1 - 2Q2) / (Q3 - Q1)
here:

Q1 = First Quartile
Q2 = Median
Q3 = Third Quartile

Theory

Bowley’s skewness is based on the relative position of the median between Q1 and Q3.

In a symmetrical distribution, the median lies exactly midway between Q1 and Q3.
If the median is not centered, the distribution is skewed.

It compares the spread of:

Upper half → (Q3 − Q2)
Lower half → (Q2 − Q1)

If both spreads are equal, the distribution is symmetric. Otherwise, skewness exists.
Interpretation
Sk = 0 → Symmetrical distribution
Sk > 0 → Positively skewed (right tail longer)
Sk < 0 → Negatively skewed (left tail longer)
Advantages
Not affected much by extreme values (outliers)
Suitable for open-ended distributions
Simple to understand and compute
Limitations
Uses only quartiles, ignoring the rest of the data
Less precise compared to other skewness measures

